	<h2>
			<a href="/index.php/79-python-resources/107-while-basics">
		While loop basics</a>
		</h2>








<p><strong>By Huy Pham</strong></p>
<p>A basic introduction to while loops</p>
<p>*************************************</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">One type of loop you may have encountered in programming</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">thus far is the 'while' loop. This loop allows for code</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">to be repeatedly excecuted infinitely, until specifically</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">told to stop, or if an error occurs. In technical terms, a</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">'while' loop is a type of control flow statement that acts as</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">a repetitive 'if' conditional statement. Let's take a look at a</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">simple 'while' loop, and break down its parts.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Stop = False</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;count = 0</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;while Stop == False:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; count += 1</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; if count = 20:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print("count is at 20")</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; elif count = 100:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;print("count is at 100")</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Stop = True</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;print('Loop has completed at: ', count)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This is the basic structure of a 'while' loop. At the top, we</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">have defined the variable 'Stop' as 'False', and the variable</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">'count' as '0'. Next we initialize a 'while' loop followed by an</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Boolean statement. As long as the Boolean statement 'Stop == False'</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">returns 'True', the 'while' loop will continue to execute.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Next we have the body of the 'while' loop, or the actual code that</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">we want to be executed continuously. The first line under the 'while'</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">loop simply adds 1 to the variable 'count' each time the loop is</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">executed. Following that is a simple 'if', 'elif' conditional statement</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">that performs certain actions when the conditions are met.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Under the 'elif' condition, we print the 'count' and change our</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">variable 'Stop' to equal 'True'. This breaks the 'while' loop by</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">negating our initial Boolean condition. The code then continues to</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">the next line after the end of the 'while' loop.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Now imagine a 'while' loop whose initial Boolean condition is always</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">satisfied. For example:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;count = 0</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;while True:&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;# 'while True:' will loop continuously</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;# until an error occurs or it is explicitly</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; count += 1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;# told to stop.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print('Line:', count)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;print('Complete')</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This code will continuously execute, and there is no variable we can</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">change in order to break the initial Boolean condition. Instead, if we</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">wanted to remove ourselves from this loop we would have to indicate a</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">condition within the loop, wait until that condition is satified, and</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">then use a 'break' line.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;count = 0</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;while True:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; count += 1</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print('Line:', count)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; if count == 50:&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;# Inserting a condition to be met here</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;break&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;# follwed by the breaking of the loop</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;print('Complete')</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Once our condition within the loop ('if' statement) is satisfied, Python</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">will 'break' our loop, and then continue onto the code after our 'while'</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">loop.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p> 
	
</div>


